\details{
SP-MCMC keeps the Stein Points objective but replaces a global search over
the whole state space with a short Markov chain. At step \code{j}, the algorithm
first chooses one of the already selected points as the start of the chain.
The chain is run for \code{m_seq[j]} states, duplicate states are removed, and
each remaining candidate \code{x} is scored by the greedy Stein Points objective.
The target score is written \eqn{s_p(x)=\nabla_x\log p(x)}, and the Stein
kernel \code{k0} is the same object described in \code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}}. For a
selected prefix \eqn{x_1,\ldots,x_m}, the running diagnostic is
\deqn{KSD_m^2 = \frac{1}{m^2}
       \sum_{a=1}^m \sum_{b=1}^m k0(x_a,x_b).}
The paper writes this objective as
\deqn{\frac{1}{2} k0(x, x) + \sum_{i=1}^{j-1} k0(x_i, x).}
The implementation uses the doubled but equivalent form
\deqn{k0(x, x) + 2 \sum_{i=1}^{j-1} k0(x_i, x),}
and the candidate with the smallest value is appended to the point set.

The first point is fixed by \code{x_init}, so \code{n_points - 1} short chains are used
to add the remaining points. A scalar \code{m_seq} is recycled as the chain length
for every update; a vector of length \code{n_points - 1} supplies the update
lengths after the first point. The built-in transitions return the chain
states, log-density values, acceptance indicators, and, for MALA, scores that
can be reused when candidates are evaluated. The algorithm maintains a
cached matrix \code{K0} with entries \code{K0[a,b]=k0(x_a,x_b)} for already selected
points; this is why start rules, candidate scoring, and KSD diagnostics can
reuse the same pairwise Stein information.

The built-in start rules are \code{"last"} for the most recently selected point,
\code{"rand"} for a random selected point, and \code{"infl"} for the point with the
smallest current influence score computed from the Stein kernel matrix. The
built-in transition kernels are Gaussian random-walk Metropolis and MALA, the
two choices used in the SP-MCMC paper. Custom \code{criterion}, \code{transition_fn},
and \code{proposal_fn} arguments expose the same pieces separately so users can
reproduce or modify the paper algorithm without rewriting the main loop.
The returned diagnostics separate MCMC evaluations from candidate scoring in
\code{counts}, report cumulative evaluations in \code{cum_n_eval}, and record
acceptance rates and squared-distance movement summaries for the short
candidate chains.

